{{Infobox website | name = Yahoo! Babel Fish | logo = Bable Fish.png | screenshot = Babel Fish.PNG | caption = | url = {{URL|babelfish.yahoo.com}} | commercial = No | type = Translation service | language = | registration = | owner = [[Yahoo!]] | launch date = {{start date and age|1997|12|9|df=no}} | current status = Defunct | revenue = }} '''Yahoo! Babel Fish''' was a free [[World Wide Web|Web]]-based multilingual translation application. In May 2012 it was replaced by [[Bing Translator]], to which queries were redirected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/translation/archive/2012/05/30/welcoming-yahoo-babel-fish-users.aspx|title=Welcome Yahoo! Babel Fish users!|publisher=Bing Translator blog|date=2012-05-31|accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref> Although Yahoo! has transitioned its Babel Fish translation services to Bing Translator, it did not sell its translation application to Microsoft outright.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/translation/archive/2012/05/30/welcoming-yahoo-babel-fish-users.aspx?PageIndex=4#comments|title=Welcoming Yahoo! Babel Fish users!|publisher=Bing Translator blog|date=2012-05-30|accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref><ref name="bing1">{{cite web | title = Yahoo's Babel Fish replaced with Bing Translator | publisher = Neowin.net, June 3, 2012, Jon Callaham | url = http://www.neowin.net/news/yahoos-babel-fish-replaced-with-bing-translator}}</ref> As the oldest free online language translator,<ref name="yahoo 2">{{cite web | title = Yahoo Launches Babel Fish | publisher = Techshout.com, April 2006 | url = http://www.techshout.com/internet/2006/28/yahoo-launches-babel-fish-the-language-translation-service/}}</ref> the service translated text or Web pages in 36 pairs between 13 languages,<ref name="yahoo 2"/> including [[English language|English]], [[Chinese language|Simplified Chinese]], [[Chinese language|Traditional Chinese]], [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Russian language|Russian]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]].
The internet service derived its name from the [[Babel fish (The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy)|Babel fish]], a fictional species in [[Douglas Adams]]'s book and radio series ''[[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]]'' that could instantly translate [[language]]s. In turn, the name of the fictional creature refers to the [[Bible|biblical]] account of the [[Confusion of tongues|confusion of language]]s that arose in the city of [[Tower of Babel|Babel]].
== History == On December 9, 1997, [[Digital Equipment Corporation]] (DEC) and [[SYSTRAN]] S.A. launched AltaVista Translation Service at babelfish.altavista.com,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.infotektur.com/demos/babelfish/en.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19990427232555/http://www.infotektur.com/demos/babelfish/en.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=1999-04-27|title=Babelfish: English|date=1999-04-27|access-date=2018-07-22}}</ref> which was developed by a team of researchers at DEC.<ref name="yahoo 2"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Edge|first=Business|url=http://www.businessedge.ca/archives/article.cfm/babelfish-on-the-move-3074/|title=BabelFish on the move - Business Edge News Magazine Archives|publisher=Businessedge.ca|date=2003-05-15|accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref> In February 2003, AltaVista was bought by [[Yahoo! Search Marketing|Overture Services, Inc.]]<ref>{{citation | last = Hansell | first = Saul | title = Overture Services to Buy AltaVista for $140 Million | newspaper = The New York Times | date = February 19, 2003 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2003/02/19/business/technology-overture-services-to-buy-altavista-for-140-million.html?exprod=permalink&partner=permalink}}</ref> In July 2003, Overture, in turn, was taken over by Yahoo!.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yahoo to acquire Overture |url=http://docs.yahoo.com/docs/pr/release1102.html |date=July 13, 2003 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708055621/http://docs.yahoo.com/docs/pr/release1102.html |archivedate=July 8, 2007 }}</ref>
The web address for Babel Fish remained at babelfish.altavista.com until May 9, 2008, when the address changed to babelfish.yahoo.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.websearchworkshop.co.uk/altavista_history.php|title=AltaVista history|publisher=Websearchworkshop.co.uk|date=1995-12-15|accessdate=2012-09-20}}</ref>
As of May 30, 2012, the Web address changed yet again, this time redirecting babelfish.yahoo.com to www.microsofttranslator.com when Microsoft's Bing Translator replaced Yahoo Babel Fish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.msdn.com/b/translation/archive/2012/05/30/welcoming-yahoo-babel-fish-users.aspx|title=Welcoming Yahoo! Babel Fish users!|publisher=Microsoft Translator (and Bing Translator) Official Team Blog|accessdate=2012-06-22}}</ref>
Yahoo! Babel Fish should not be confused with The Babel Fish Corporation founded by [[Oscar Jofre]],<ref>{{cite web|title=BabelFish continues to grow international presence|url=http://canadait.ca/cfm/index.cfm?It=106&Id=14925&Se=2&Lo=442|date=March 7, 2003|accessdate=2012-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208210045/http://canadait.ca/cfm/index.cfm?It=106&Id=14925&Se=2&Lo=442|archive-date=2016-02-08|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> which was operated at the URL [https://www.babelfish.com www.babelfish.com] (created in 1995).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwhois.com/babelfish.com|title=Public Whois of BabelFish|publisher=Verisign Registry|accessdate=2012-07-20}}</ref>
As of June 2013, babelfish.yahoo.com no longer redirected to the Microsoft Bing Translator. Instead, it refers directly back to the main Yahoo.com page.
