==Numbers==

===Cardinal numbers===
There are three kinds of cardinal numbers in Irish: disjunctive numbers, nonhuman conjunctive numbers, and human conjunctive numbers.

====Disjunctive numbers====
{|
| width=20 | 0
| width=150 | {{Lang|ga|náid}}
| width=30 | 13
| width=150 | {{Lang|ga|a trí déag}}
|-
| 1 || {{Lang|ga|a haon}} || 14 || {{Lang|ga|a ceathair déag}}
|-
| 2 || {{Lang|ga|a dó}} || 20 || {{Lang|ga|fiche}}
|-
| 3 || {{Lang|ga|a trí}} || 21 || {{Lang|ga|fiche a haon}}
|-
| 4 || {{Lang|ga|a ceathair}} || 30 || {{Lang|ga|tríocha}}
|-
| 5 || {{Lang|ga|a cúig}} || 40 || {{Lang|ga|daichead}}
|-
| 6 || {{Lang|ga|a sé}} || 50 || {{Lang|ga|caoga}}
|-
| 7 || {{Lang|ga|a seacht}} || 60 || {{Lang|ga|seasca}}
|-
| 8 || {{Lang|ga|a hocht}} || 70 || {{Lang|ga|seachtó}}
|-
| 9 || {{Lang|ga|a naoi}} || 80 || {{Lang|ga|ochtó}}
|-
| 10 || {{Lang|ga|a deich}} || 90 || {{Lang|ga|nócha}}
|-
| 11 || {{Lang|ga|a haon déag}} || 100 || {{Lang|ga|céad}}
|-
| 12 || {{Lang|ga|a dó dhéag}} || 1000. || {{Lang|ga|míle}}
|}
These numbers are used for example in arithmetic, in telling time, in telephone numbers and after nouns in forms like {{Lang|ga|bus a trí déag}} "bus 13" or {{Lang|ga|seomra a dó}} "room 2".

====Nonhuman conjunctive numbers====
These numbers are used to count nouns that do not refer to human beings, e.g. {{Lang|ga|capall}} "horse"
{|
| width=20 | 1
| width=150 | {{Lang|ga|aon chapall amháin}};<br />{{Lang|ga|capall amháin}}
| width=20 | 13
| width=150 | {{Lang|ga|trí chapall déag}}
|-
| 2 || {{Lang|ga|dhá chapall}} || 20 || {{Lang|ga|fiche capall}}
|-
| 3 || {{Lang|ga|trí chapall}} || 21 || {{Lang|ga|capall is fiche}}
|-
| 4 || {{Lang|ga|ceithre chapall}} || 22 || {{Lang|ga|dhá chapall is fiche}}
|-
| 5 || {{Lang|ga|cúig chapall}} || 30 || {{Lang|ga|tríocha capall}}
|-
| 6 || {{Lang|ga|sé chapall}} || 40 || {{Lang|ga|daichead capall}}
|-
| 7 || {{Lang|ga|seacht gcapall}} || 50 || {{Lang|ga|caoga capall}}
|-
| 8 || {{Lang|ga|ocht gcapall}} || 60 || {{Lang|ga|seasca capall}}
|-
| 9 || {{Lang|ga|naoi gcapall}} || 70 || {{Lang|ga|seachtó capall}}
|-
| 10 || {{Lang|ga|deich gcapall}} || 80 || {{Lang|ga|ochtó capall}}
|-
| 11 || {{Lang|ga|aon chapall déag}} || 90 || {{Lang|ga|nócha capall}}
|-
| 12 || {{Lang|ga|dhá chapall déag}} || 100 || {{Lang|ga|céad capall}}
|}
"One" as a [[pronoun]] is rendered with {{Lang|ga|ceann}} (lit. "head") when it concerns things and animals, e.g.:
:{{Lang|ga|Tá cúig chapall agam; tá ceann acu breoite.}} "I have five horses; one of them is sick."

====Human conjunctive numbers====
These numbers are used to count nouns that refer to human beings, e.g. '''páiste''' 'child'
{|
| width=20 | 1
| width=150 | {{Lang|ga|aon pháiste amháin}};<br />{{Lang|ga|páiste amháin}}
| width=20 | 7
| width=150 | {{Lang|ga|seachtar páistí}}
|-
| 2 || {{Lang|ga|beirt pháistí}} || 8 || {{Lang|ga|ochtar páistí}}
|-
| 3 || {{Lang|ga|triúr páistí}} || 9 || {{Lang|ga|naonúr páistí}}
|-
| 4 || {{Lang|ga|ceathrar páistí}} || 10 || {{Lang|ga|deichniúr páistí}}
|-
| 5 || {{Lang|ga|cúigear páistí}} || 11 || {{Lang|ga|aon pháiste déag}}
|-
| 6 || {{Lang|ga|seisear páistí}} || 12 || {{Lang|ga|dáréag páistí}}
|}
"One" as a pronoun is rendered with {{Lang|ga|duine}} (lit. "person") with people. The other "personal" numbers can also be used pronominally, e.g.:
:{{Lang|ga|Tá cúigear páistí agam; tá duine acu breoite.}} "I have five children; one of them is sick."
:{{Lang|ga|Tá seisear sa seomra.}} "Six people are in the room."

Higher numbers are done as with the nonhuman conjunctive numbers: {{Lang|ga|trí pháiste déag}}, {{lang|ga|fiche páiste}}, etc.

